<div class="content">
    <section>
        <p>
            The Go programming language is well-known and often chosen for its
            powerful concurrency features. However, writing concurrent programs
            remains challenging and prone to subtle bugs. While the Go runtime
            detects <span class="code">global deadlocks</span> and terminates the
            program immediately, <span class="code">partial deadlocks</span> go
            unnoticed. These can lead to <span class="code">memory leaks</span>
            that necessitate frequent restarts of production services. Go 1.26
            addresses this issue by introducing a new experimental profile that
            leverages the Go garbage collector to detect a wide class of partial
            deadlocks at runtime.
        </p>
        <p>
            This article explores the new, experimental
            <span style="font-style: italic">goroutineleakprofile</span>, its
            theoretical background, how to make use of it, and its limitations.
        </p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h3>Concurrency in Go</h3>
        <p>
            The Go programming language is particularly famous for its concurrency
            features. It introduces <span style="font-style: italic">goroutines</span>,
            which are lightweight threads managed and multiplexed by the Go
            runtime onto operating system threads. This allows programs to handle
            many concurrent operations with minimal overhead. Goroutines may block
            when performing operations on concurrency constructs or during system
            calls (e.g., network or disk IO), at which point the runtime puts
            them in a waiting state until the necessary unblocking conditions
            are met.
        </p>
        <p>
            Go provides two primary paradigms for synchronizing goroutines:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Message Passing</strong>: Using
                <span class="keyword">chan T</span> to communicate. Goroutines
                block when sending to or receiving from a channel until a
                complementary operation occurs. Unbuffered channels require
                synchronization between sender and receiver, while buffered
                channels allow asynchronous communication until the buffer is
                full or empty. The <span class="keyword">select</span> statement
                allows a goroutine to wait on multiple channel operations
                simultaneously.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Shared Memory</strong>: Using the
                <a
                    href="https://pkg.go.dev/sync"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                >
                    <span class="datapoint">sync</span>
                </a>
                package to manage access to shared state. This includes
                <a
                    href="https://pkg.go.dev/sync#Mutex"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                >
                    <span class="datapoint">mutexes</span>
                </a>
                for mutual exclusion,
                <a
                    href="https://pkg.go.dev/sync#Cond"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                >
                    <span class="datapoint">condition variables</span>
                </a>
                for signaling, and
                <a
                    href="https://pkg.go.dev/sync#WaitGroup"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                >
                    <span class="datapoint">wait groups</span>
                </a>
                to synchronize the completion of multiple goroutines.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            A goroutine blocked at any of these operations may only be unblocked
            by another goroutine performing a complementary action. While Go
            provides intuitive primitives for concurrency, writing robust
            concurrent software remains challenging and prone to subtle bugs.
        </p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h3>Global and partial deadlocks</h3>
        <p>
            A program encounters a <span class="datapoint">global deadlock</span>
            whenever all its goroutines are blocked, waiting to be able to perform
            an operation on one or more concurrency constructs. Global deadlocks
            are detected by the Go runtime, which immediately terminates the
            program.
        </p>
        <p>
            The following example demonstrates a global deadlock in action:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-go">{% include "articles/goroutine_leak_detection/global-deadlock.go" %}</code></pre>
        <p>
            The goroutine at line 10 blocks on the channel operation
            <span class="keyword">&lt; dataReady</span> at line 12. The main goroutine
            blocks on the wait group operation
            <span class="keyword">wg.Wait()</span> at line 16. Neither can proceed.
            Running the above program will result in a global deadlock and the
            program will be immediately terminated:
        </p>
        <pre><code class="language-shell">{% include "articles/goroutine_leak_detection/global-deadlock-output.txt" %}</code></pre>
        <p>
            A program encounters a <span class="datapoint">partial deadlock</span>
            whenever some goroutines are blocked, but not all. Partial deadlocks
            are not detected by the Go runtime and the program will continue to
            run indefinitely.
            <span style="text-decoration: underline;">
                While global deadlocks are quite rare in production
                systems, partial deadlocks are not, and can lead to memeory leaks, as
                deadlocked goroutines will hang on to resources indefinitely.
            </span>
        </p>
    </section>
